HIV/AIDS: China reported a 14% increase in new cases
China reported a 14% jump in the number of new cases of people living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people in the country have been hit, health officials say.
About 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases have been transmitted through sexual relations, which is a change over the previous situation.
Usually in the past, HIV spread rapidly to some parts of China as a result of blood transfusions infected with the virus.
However, the number of people who receive HIV this way is reduced to almost zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan Province.
From year to year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a worsening problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality has no longer been considered illegal in China since 1997, but they say LGBT discrimination is very widespread.
Studies estimate that because of conservative perceptions in the country, 70-90% of men who have sex with men end up marrying women.
The transmission of the virus is often also due to inadequate sexual protection in such relations.
In 2003, the Chinese government pledged universal access to HIV medicines as part of a plan to address this problem.
